would be a margin and they might all take their 
time. At present, before long (by the time he 
should be ready), the question of Miss Francina's 
leaving Paris for the summer would be sure to 
come up, and that would be a tiresome interrup- 
tion. She liked Paris, she had no plans for the 
autumn and only wanted a reason to come back 
about the twentieth of September. Mr. Waterlow 
remarked humorously that she evidently bossed 



