that strange, lovely girl, whom he liked so much 
and whose companions he failed to like, that he 
felt supremely without a vocation. Freshness 
was there at least, if he had only had the method. 
He prayed eaniestly, in relation to methods, for 
a providential reinforcement of Waterlow's sense 
of this quality. If Waterlow had a fault it was 
that he was sometimes a little stale. 

He avenged himself for the artist's bewildering 
